<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<section xml:id="4-3-26" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>4-3-26</title>
    <p>Generated <m>\sigma</m>-Algebras, Borel Sets, Carathéodory Criterion.</p>

    <example>
        <p>Let <m>\mathcal F \subseteq \mathcal P(\R)</m> such that <me>\mathcal F = \{A \subseteq \R \mid \textrm{either } A \textrm{ open or } A \textrm{ closed}\}</me>.</p>
        <p>Since <m>\mathcal F</m> is not closed under countable unions (or even finite unions) <m>\mathcal F</m> is not a <m>\sigma</m>-algebra.</p>
    </example>

    <definition xml:id="def-gen-sigma-alg">
        <title><m>\sigma</m>-Algebra Generated by <m>\mathcal F</m></title>
        <p>
            Let <m>\mathcal F \subseteq \mathcal P(X)</m> be a collection of subsets of <m>X</m>. Let <m>\sigma(\mathcal F)</m> be the smallest <m>\sigma</m>-algebra on <m>X</m> containing <m>\mathcal F</m>.
        </p>
        <p>Call <m>\sigma(\mathcal F)</m> the <m>\sigma</m>-algebra <em>generated</em> by <m>\mathcal F</m>.</p>
    </definition>

    <definition xml:id="def-borel">
        <title>Borel <m>\sigma</m>-Algebra</title>
        <p>
            Let <m>\mathcal B = \sigma(\{\textrm{open sets}\}) = \sigma(\{\textrm{closed sets}\})</m>. Then, <m>\mathcal B</m> is called the <em>Borel <m>\sigma</m>-algebra</em>.
        </p>
        <p>The elements of <m>\mathcal B</m> are called <em>Borel sets</em>.</p>
    </definition>

    <example>
        <p>Let <m>\mathcal F = \{[1, 2 - \frac{1}{n}] \mid n \in \N\}</m> be a collection of closed sets. <m>\bigcup_{n = 1}^\infty [1, 2 - \frac{1}{n}] = [1, 2)</m>. Consequently, <m>\mathcal F</m> is not closed under countable unions and is not a <m>\sigma</m>-algebra.</p>
    </example>

    <example>
        <p>Let <m>X = \{1, 2, 3, 4, 5\}</m>. Let <m>\mathcal F = \{\{1, 3\}\}</m>. Then, <me>\sigma(\mathcal F) = \{\emptyset, X, \{1, 3\}, \{2, 4, 5\}\}</me>.</p>
    </example>

    <definition xml:id="def-borel-sig-alg-msr-sets">
        <title>Borel <m>\sigma</m>-Algebra of Lebesgue Measurable Sets</title>
        <p>Let <m>\mathcal M</m> be the <m>\sigma</m>-algebra on <m>\R</m> generated by Borel sets and null sets.</p>
        <p>Later we will see that <m>\mathcal M</m> is the <m>\sigma</m>-algebra of Lebesgue measurable sets.</p>
        <p>We sometimes call <m>\mathcal M</m> the <em>completion</em> of <m>\mathcal B</m>.</p>
    </definition>

    <definition xml:id="def-caratheodory-crit">
        <title>Carathéodory Criterion</title>
        <p>We say <m>A \subseteq \R</m> is in <m>\mathcal M_0</m> if for any subset <m>X \subseteq \R</m> <me>\mu^*(X) = \mu^*(X \cap A) + \mu^*(X \cap A^{\mathsf c})</me>.</p>
        <p><m>\mathcal M_0</m> is equivalent to <m>\mathcal M</m> and is also the <m>\sigma</m>-algebra of Lebesgue measurable sets.</p>
    </definition>

    <remark>
        <p>We always have <m>\mu^*(X) \le \mu^*(X \cap A) + \mu^*(X \cap A^{\mathsf c})</m> by countable subadditivity. Consequently, to show that <m>A \in \mathcal M_0</m>, it suffices to prove <m>\mu^*(X) \ge \mu^*(X \cap A) + \mu^*(X \cap A^{\mathsf c})</m>.</p>
        <p>We will also see that Borel sets and null sets satisfy the Carathéodory Criterion.</p>
    </remark>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-msr-null-sets">
        <title>Measurability of Null Sets</title>
        <p>Null sets are measurable.</p>
        <proof>
            <p>Let <m>A \subset \R</m> be a null set. Take any <m>A \subseteq \R</m>. Then, <me>\mu^*(X \cap A) + \mu^*(X \cap A^{\mathsf c}) \underset{\textrm{M.}}{\le} + \mu^*(A) + \mu^*(X \cap A^{\mathsf c}) \underset{\textrm{M.}}{\le} 0 + \mu^*(X)</me>.</p>
        </proof>
    </proposition>

    <observation xml:id="obs-M0-first-two-sigma-alg">
        <title><m>\mathcal M_0</m> Satifies First Two Properties of <m>\sigma</m>-Algebras</title>
        <p><m>A \in \mathcal M_0</m> if and only if <m>A^{\mathsf c} \in \mathcal M_0</m>.</p>
        <p><m>\emptyset \in \mathcal M_0</m> so <m>\R \in \mathcal M_0</m>.</p>
        <p>Thus, <m>\mathcal M_0</m> satisfies the first two properties of <m>\sigma</m>-algebras outlined in <xref ref="def-sigma-algebras"/>. It remains to show that <m>\mathcal M_0</m> is closed under countable unions.</p>
    </observation>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-M0-finite-unions">
        <title>Finite Unions of <m>\mathcal M_0</m></title>
        <p>Let <m>A, B \in \mathcal M_0</m>. Then, <m>A \cup B \in \mathcal M_0</m>.</p>
        <proof>
            <p>
                Note that <md>X \cap (A \cup B) = (X \cap B) \cup (X \cap A \cap B^{\mathsf c})</md>. Additionally, <md>
                    <mrow>\mu^*(X \cap B^{\mathsf c}) \amp = \mu^*((X \cap B^{\mathsf c}) \cap A) + \mu^*((X \cap B^{\mathsf c}) \cap A^{\mathsf c})</mrow>
                    <mrow number = "yes">\amp = \mu^*(X \cap B^{\mathsf c} \cap A) + \mu^*(X \cap (A \cup B)^{\mathsf c})</mrow>
                </md> where the first equality holds from <m>A \in \mathcal M_0</m> and the second from <m>B^{\mathsf c} \cap A^{\mathsf c} = (A \cup B)^{\mathsf c}</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Consequently, <md>
                    <mrow>\mu^*(X \cap (A \cup B)) + \mu^*(X \cap (A \cup B)^{\mathsf c}) \amp \underset{\textrm{S.A.}}{\le} \mu^*(X \cap B) + \mu^*(X \cap A \cap B^{\mathsf c})</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp \phantom{\underset{\textrm{S.A.}}{\le}} + \mu^*(X \cap (A \cup B)^{\mathsf c})</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp= \mu^*(A \cap B) + \mu^*(X \cap B^{\mathsf c})</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp = \mu^*(X)</mrow>
                </md>. Thus, <m>\mu^*(X \cap (A \cup B)) + \mu^*(X \cap (A \cup B)^{\mathsf c}) \le \mu^*(X)</m>, as required.
            </p>
        </proof>
    </proposition>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-disjoint-M0">
        <title>Disjoint Elements of <m>\mathcal M_0</m></title>
        <p>Let <m>A, B \in \mathcal M_0</m> be disjoint. Then, for any <m>X \subseteq \R</m>, <me>\mu^*(X \cap (A \cup B)) = \mu^*(X \cap A) + \mu^*(X \cap B)</me>.</p>
        <proof>
            <md>
                <mrow>\mu^*(X \cap (A \cup B)) \amp = \mu^*(X \cap (A \cup B) \cap A) + \mu^*(X \cap (A \cup B) \cap A^{\mathsf c})</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp = \mu^*(X \cap A) + \mu^*(X \cap B)</mrow>
            </md>.
        </proof>
    </proposition>

    <corollary xml:id="cor-finite-add-disjoint-M0">
        <title>Finite Additivity of Disjoint Elements of <m>\mathcal M_0</m></title>
        <p>Let <m>X = \R</m>. If <m>A, B \in \mathcal M_0</m>, <m>A \cap B = \emptyset</m>, we have <m>\mu^*(A \cup B) = \mu^*(A) + \mu^*(B)</m> from <xref ref="prop-disjoint-M0"/> and <xref ref="def-caratheodory-crit"/>. Thus, for measurable sets <m>A, B \in \mathcal M_0</m> that are disjoint, we have finite additivity.</p>
    </corollary>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-M0-closed-countable-union">
        <title>Closedness of <m>\mathcal M_0</m> Under Countable Unions</title>
        <p>Let <m>\{A_i\}_{i = 1}^\infty \subseteq \mathcal M_0</m>. Then, <m>\bigcup_{i = 1}^\infty A_i \in \mathcal M_0</m>.</p>
        <proof>
            <p>Let <m>E_k = \bigcup_{j = 1}^k A_j</m>, let <m>B_k = A_k \backslash E_{k - 1} = A_k \cap (E_{k - 1})^{\mathsf c}</m> for <m>k > 1</m>, and assume <m>A_1 = E_1 = B_1</m>.</p>
            <p>Firstly, <m>E_\infty = \bigcup_{i = 1}^\infty A_i</m>. Then, <m>E_\infty = \bigcup_{i = 1}^\infty B_i</m> as well. Finally, <m>B_i \cap B_j = \emptyset</m> if <m>i \ne j</m>, so the set of <m>B_i</m> is pairwise disjoint.</p>
            <p>
                Given <m>X \subseteq \R</m> and <m>N \in \N</m>, <md>
                    <mrow>\mu^*(X) \amp = \mu^*(X \cap B_N) + \mu^*(X \cap E_N^{\mathsf c})</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp \underset{\textrm{M.}}{\ge} \mu^*(X \cap E_N) + \mu^*(X \cap E_\infty^{\mathsf c})</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp = \sum_{i = 1}^{N} \mu^*(X \cap B_i) + \mu^*(X \cap E_\infty^{\mathsf c})</mrow>
                    </md> where the final inequality holds from <xef ref="cor-finite-add-disjoint-M0"/>.
            </p>
            <p>Since this holds for all <m>N \in \N</m>, it follows that <md>
                <mrow>\mu^*(X) \amp \ge \sum_{i = 1}^{\infty} \mu^*(X \cap B_i) + \mu^*(X \cap E_\infty^{\mathsf c})</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp \underset{\textrm{S.A.}}{\ge} \mu^*\left(\bigcup_{i = 1}^\infty (X \cap B_i)\right) + \mu^*(X \cap E_\infty^{\mathsf c})</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp = \mu^*(X \cap E_\infty) + \mu^*(X \cap E_\infty^{\mathsf c})</mrow>
            </md> so <m>E_\infty</m> is measurable.</p>
            <p>As <m>E_\infty = bigcup_{i = 1}^\infty A</m>, it follows that <m>\bigcup_{i = 1}^\infty A \in \mathcal M_0</m>, as required.</p>
        </proof>
    </proposition>

    <corollary xml:id="cor-M0-sigma-alg">
        <title><m>\mathcal M_0</m> is a <m>\sigma</m>-Algebra</title>
        <p>From <xref ref="obs-M0-first-two-sigma-alg"/> and <xref ref="prop-M0-closed-countable-union"/>, <m>\mathcal M_0</m> is a <m>\sigma</m>-algebra.</p>
    </corollary>
</section>
